    "body": "## AI Disclosure\r\n\r\nThis change was generated with Codex. I am not familiar with the codebase. But the change is working for me, so I figured I could share it. Happy to get extra edits or a different PR with the same changes, personally what I needed is to avoid spawning 2 LSPs\r\n\r\n## Problem\r\n\r\nWhen `vim.lsp.start` is called twice for the same buffer/root_dir, `ruby_lsp` fails to dedup and a second LSP process is spawned.\r\n\r\nI hit this with lazy.nvim: any `ft = \"ruby\"` plugin causes `vim.lsp.start` to fire twice. Once on the initial `FileType` event, and again after lazy.nvim loads the plugin and replays `FileType`. End result: two `ruby_lsp` processes attached to the same buffer.\r\n\r\n```lua\r\n-- lazy.nvim spec that triggers it\r\n{\r\n  \"neovim/nvim-lspconfig\",\r\n  opts = { servers = { ruby_lsp = { cmd = { \"mise\", \"x\", \"--\", \"ruby-lsp\" } } } },\r\n},\r\n{ \"tpope/vim-rails\", ft = \"ruby\" },\r\n```\r\n\r\nBut it's not lazy.nvim-specific. Any double call to `vim.lsp.start` for the same root reproduces it:\r\n\r\n```lua\r\nvim.lsp.start({ name = \"ruby_lsp\", cmd = { \"ruby-lsp\" }, root_dir = \"/tmp/x\" })\r\nvim.lsp.start({ name = \"ruby_lsp\", cmd = { \"ruby-lsp\" }, root_dir = \"/tmp/x\" })\r\n-- :LspInfo → two ruby_lsp clients, two processes\r\n```\r\n\r\n## Cause\r\n\r\nThe current `reuse_client` mutates the *incoming* config and then compares it against the *existing* client:\r\n\r\n```lua\r\nreuse_client = function(client, config)\r\n  config.cmd_cwd = config.root_dir\r\n  return client.name == config.name and client.config.cmd_cwd == config.cmd_cwd\r\nend,\r\n```\r\n\r\n`cmd_cwd` is never set on the existing client. It's not in the default spec, and mutating the new `config` doesn't propagate back to `client.config`. So `client.config.cmd_cwd` is `nil`, the comparison fails, and dedup never happens.\r\n\r\n## Fix\r\n\r\nCompare `root_dir` directly. Both sides have it.\r\n\r\n```lua\r\nreuse_client = function(client, config)\r\n  config.cmd_cwd = config.root_dir\r\n  return client.name == config.name and client.config.root_dir == config.root_dir\r\nend,\r\n```\r\n\r\nThe `config.cmd_cwd = config.root_dir` line is kept to preserve existing behavior, but it appears to be dead code in this file: `cmd` is defined as a function that already does `cwd = config.cmd_cwd or config.root_dir` on every spawn, so the process cwd is correctly set whether or not the mutation runs. It could likely be removed in a follow-up.\r\n\r\n## Note on `ast_grep`\r\n\r\n`lsp/ast_grep.lua` has the same `reuse_client` pattern (introduced together in #4099 / #4408). It's intentionally left out of this PR because, unlike `ruby_lsp`, `ast_grep`'s `cmd` is a static array and relies on `cmd_cwd` for process cwd. Removing the mutation there has a tangible (if narrow) behavioral effect, so it deserves its own discussion.\r\n",
